No, we're gonna stick
on the actual track.

46:40.280 --> 46:43.200
Ah, little bit. Don't let it
get too sideways, Rory!

46:45.440 --> 46:47.640
Yep, that's beautifully
held through there.

46:49.160 --> 46:51.560
Smooth power application,
yep.

46:51.600 --> 46:54.560
More of it.
Should have done this,
you're in the wrong sport.

46:54.600 --> 46:56.080
Ah, I dunno.

46:56.120 --> 46:57.560
No, this is looking
very good indeed.

46:57.600 --> 46:59.480
Are we gonna be able
to control it here?

46:59.520 --> 47:02.000
Very nice in,
keeping it to the right.

47:02.040 --> 47:04.080
Which puts you in the right
place for that left.

47:04.120 --> 47:06.800
You've managed to keep
two tyres on the track,
so that's all right.

47:06.840 --> 47:08.240
And off we go.

47:08.280 --> 47:10.280
OK, come on,
lift a little, turn in!

47:12.040 --> 47:13.640
Probably not flat
through there today.

47:13.680 --> 47:15.240
It's too slippery, too icy.

47:15.280 --> 47:17.000
RORY: Here's the corner
we were having trouble with.

47:17.040 --> 47:19.400
JEREMY: This is the tricky
one, the last corner.

47:19.440 --> 47:22.480
Ooh, bit of understeer
but just keeping it...

47:22.520 --> 47:23.880
Oh, no!

47:23.920 --> 47:26.440
Just about made it
across the line!

47:28.000 --> 47:29.240
Oh, yeah.

47:31.800 --> 47:33.160
So there we are.

47:35.360 --> 47:37.520
Right, so just so you know,

47:37.560 --> 47:39.280
I've got some times
we've had.

47:39.320 --> 47:42.440
Fastest so far 1:17,
Kevin Pietersen.

47:42.480 --> 47:45.600
Slowest, Dynamo,
last week, 1.39.3.

47:45.640 --> 47:48.000
But the track was
two feet deep in snow

47:48.040 --> 47:49.640
so he has got an excuse.

47:49.680 --> 47:51.080
-Oh, my goodness.
-He does.

47:51.120 --> 47:52.920
Got your times here.

47:52.960 --> 47:54.920
Paris Hilton...

47:56.400 --> 47:58.600
1.25.8.

47:58.640 --> 48:01.640
So that puts you - have
a round of applause for that.

48:04.000 --> 48:06.040
You're faster than two people
you've never heard of:

48:06.080 --> 48:11.280
Alfie Boe and Bill Bailey
are both, well, round
about that sort of time, OK?

48:11.320 --> 48:15.720
1.25.8, that's the time
you've gotta beat
on a greasy track, Rory.

48:17.680 --> 48:19.600
One...

48:19.640 --> 48:21.960
21...

48:22.000 --> 48:23.720
-Ooh.
-...point 9.

48:23.760 --> 48:25.520
That is a very good time.

48:26.720 --> 48:28.400
Very good time.

48:30.880 --> 48:32.160
Faster than Hugh Bonneville.

48:32.200 --> 48:35.360
-There you go.
-Faster than Hugh Bonneville,
and he was on a dry track.

48:35.400 --> 48:37.320
So that was extremely good.

48:37.360 --> 48:40.080
-I can't thank you enough
for coming, I really can't.
-Thank you for having us.

48:40.120 --> 48:42.000
Pleasure to have you here.
Ladies and gentlemen,

48:42.040 --> 48:46.480
Paris Hilton, and the world's
fastest golfing enthusiast,
Rory McIlroy!

48:51.560 --> 48:54.320
Now. Now.

48:54.360 --> 48:57.080
Earlier on,
we were in Canada,

48:57.120 --> 48:59.480
where we proved that
medium-sized SUVs

48:59.520 --> 49:01.760
are useless at everything.

49:01.800 --> 49:06.400
But Mr Willman said the tests
we'd done were idiotic.

49:06.440 --> 49:09.240
Yeah, he said people actually
buy them to go canoeing

49:09.280 --> 49:11.400
and hiking
and mountain biking,

49:11.440 --> 49:14.440
and he then also said
that we could only come home

49:14.480 --> 49:17.360
once we'd completed
one more challenge.

49:32.400 --> 49:35.200
JAMES: Why are we
towing speedboats?

49:35.240 --> 49:36.480
Never mind that, James.

49:36.520 --> 49:39.320
Why have you bought
a brown speedboat?

49:39.360 --> 49:41.400
Er, it's orange.

49:41.440 --> 49:43.240
Never mind James's
brown speed boat,

49:43.280 --> 49:45.400
where's your Alfa Romeo?

49:45.440 --> 49:47.880
It was stolen.

49:47.920 --> 49:49.640
-No, it wasn't.
- It was!

49:49.680 --> 49:52.920
I came out of the hotel this
morning, it was just gone.
Literally gone.

49:52.960 --> 49:56.360
You know Canada is number one
in the world for car theft?

49:56.400 --> 49:57.680
No, it isn't.

49:57.720 --> 49:59.800
So what I've done
is I've replaced it

49:59.840 --> 50:02.880
with this Ford F150
pickup truck,

50:02.920 --> 50:05.760
which is the best-selling
vehicle, not just in Canada,

50:05.800 --> 50:08.040
but the entire world.

50:08.080 --> 50:11.760
Yeah, but the fact is
you've replaced your Alfa

50:11.800 --> 50:14.240
because we were told
to tow speedboats

50:14.280 --> 50:16.800
and you can't fit
a towbar to a Stelvio.

50:18.160 --> 50:21.320
The problem is that they've
routed the exhaust

50:21.360 --> 50:22.680
on the Stelvio in such a way

50:22.720 --> 50:25.160
that you can't, actually, as
Hammond says, fit a towbar.

50:25.200 --> 50:27.480
I think the thing is,

50:27.520 --> 50:31.480
that in Italy it's unmanly
and undignified
to tow something.

50:32.600 --> 50:34.080
I mean, why would
they tow something?

50:34.120 --> 50:35.280
It just slows you down.

50:38.000 --> 50:40.240
Soon, we arrived
at the start point

50:40.280 --> 50:42.360
for Mr Willman's challenge.

50:42.400 --> 50:45.920
Which was precisely
in the middle of nowhere.

50:48.400 --> 50:50.320
JEREMY: James...

50:50.360 --> 50:51.720
This is a skip.

50:51.760 --> 50:53.640
No, it's just all stuff
that was thrown in.

50:53.680 --> 50:55.760
Literally thrown in, yeah.

50:55.800 --> 50:58.560
-It's all boat stuff.
There's a traffic cone.

50:58.600 --> 51:00.600
Well, that's probably
something to do with boating.

51:00.640 --> 51:02.080
It isn't anything
to do with boating!

51:02.120 --> 51:03.960
This is an oar
and a boat suit and...

51:04.000 --> 51:06.080
-Looking for bears.

51:06.120 --> 51:07.440
Why?

51:07.480 --> 51:10.360
Because one of the
things I don't wanna be
is eaten by a bear.

51:10.400 --> 51:12.640
I wouldn't worry about
being eaten by one.

51:12.680 --> 51:14.000
Well, I do.

51:14.040 --> 51:15.480
Well,
they do far worse than that.

51:15.520 --> 51:18.240
-Hang on, hang on,
we have a message,

51:18.280 --> 51:20.120
and it's from Mr Willman.

51:20.160 --> 51:23.920
"Each of your cars
has been fitted with
a satellite compass

51:23.960 --> 51:25.880
which will direct you
to the finish line.

51:25.920 --> 51:30.040
Whoever arrives first can
claim to have the best SUV."

51:30.080 --> 51:31.320
Well, that's me.

51:31.360 --> 51:33.360
Well, apart from
you haven't got an SUV.

51:33.400 --> 51:35.080
It's got a twin
turbo-charged V6 -

51:35.120 --> 51:36.400
same as the Alfa.

51:36.440 --> 51:38.120
Four-wheel drive,
same as the Alfa.

51:38.160 --> 51:40.520
It's exactly the same colour.

51:40.560 --> 51:43.600
JEREMY: With all that
cleared up... the race began.

51:43.640 --> 51:45.960
-Ah!

51:46.000 --> 51:47.680
Right, where are we
now? There.

51:47.720 --> 51:51.680
My compass thing
says I've gotta go
in that direction

51:51.720 --> 51:53.800
for 5.1 kilometres.

51:54.960 --> 51:56.960
How hard can that be?

52:00.400 --> 52:04.760
Come on, little Porsche,
this is your chance to show
your off-road credentials.

52:04.800 --> 52:07.800
The Porsche is the only one
with a proper four-wheel
drive system for this.

52:07.840 --> 52:10.200
It can divert all of its
power to the front wheels

52:10.240 --> 52:12.720
so it can scrabble its way
out of trouble like a dog,

52:12.760 --> 52:14.440
pulling itself
with its front legs.

52:16.600 --> 52:20.720
Right. Typical of those two,
just roar off
being brilliant.

52:20.760 --> 52:23.040
Let's have a look
at the map first.

52:26.520 --> 52:28.360
Might just go
straight up here.

52:28.400 --> 52:30.440
Through these nettles.

52:30.480 --> 52:32.840
What are they,
Christmas trees?
I don't know what they are.

52:37.760 --> 52:39.800
If you really want
to go off-road,

52:39.840 --> 52:41.600
you need a real off-roader.

52:41.640 --> 52:45.680
A Range Rover,
a Land Cruiser, a Raptor.

52:45.720 --> 52:47.960
There's no point messing
around with a little SUV.

52:48.000 --> 52:49.240
It's not gonna go anywhere.

52:50.400 --> 52:51.640
Speaking of which...

52:56.080 --> 52:57.800
RICHARD: Oh, I'm stuck.

52:57.840 --> 53:00.000
I'm going backwards now.

53:03.680 --> 53:09.200
So I'm going west-northwest.
That's high terrain...

53:09.240 --> 53:11.720
That's very high,
I want to avoid that.
I should try to...

53:14.840 --> 53:16.440
Come on, come on.

53:22.280 --> 53:25.000
Four-wheel drive overload,
rear-wheel drive only.

53:25.040 --> 53:26.680
Reduce engine load.

53:26.720 --> 53:28.360
It doesn't work!

53:28.400 --> 53:30.600
I need another route.

53:30.640 --> 53:34.320
RICHARD: James, meanwhile,
had sorted out his route

53:34.360 --> 53:36.800
and was now
sorting out his car.

53:36.840 --> 53:40.640
I'm putting my
response system
in grass, gravel and snow.

53:40.680 --> 53:42.160
It has just started snowing.

53:42.200 --> 53:43.480
-I also have--

53:43.520 --> 53:45.520
Who the hell is that?

53:45.560 --> 53:47.520
It's Hammond, look,
he's got exactly nowhere.

53:48.840 --> 53:50.240
What a spanner.

53:50.280 --> 53:52.880
Anyway.

53:52.920 --> 53:55.880
JEREMY: With both
my colleagues still
on the start line,

53:55.920 --> 53:58.320
I was winning by miles.

54:00.080 --> 54:02.320
This is a very narrow
little path, this one.

54:02.360 --> 54:04.280
I don't want to be
making a mess... Oh, hello.

54:06.080 --> 54:07.560
Right.

54:07.600 --> 54:10.880
What that is
is a fallen-down tree.

54:10.920 --> 54:13.520
How the hell do you
reverse a trailer?

54:16.320 --> 54:18.760
So if I turn the steering
wheel this way...

54:21.040 --> 54:23.760
This way.

54:23.800 --> 54:26.120
Yeah, I've got it,
I've got it.

54:28.120 --> 54:30.320
This is a bit... No, not...

54:30.360 --> 54:33.640
Oh, shit, no! Ooh, God!

54:37.280 --> 54:39.800
Boat is still attached,
correct.

54:39.840 --> 54:42.400
Direction, roughly right.

54:42.440 --> 54:44.440
Everything's excellent.

54:46.120 --> 54:47.760
Plenty of power,
this is good.

54:50.000 --> 54:52.080
Right,
arrow's pointing that way.

54:55.520 --> 54:57.280
Now we're making progress.

54:58.840 --> 55:02.400
I want to go...
If I turn into the...

55:04.840 --> 55:06.120
No, this way.

55:09.320 --> 55:11.120
Oh, Christ, that's not right.

55:11.160 --> 55:13.920
JEREMY: Having carefully
unhitched the trailer...

55:14.920 --> 55:16.080
Right.

55:16.120 --> 55:19.280
I was soon turned round
and back on the move

55:19.320 --> 55:22.400
looking for another route.

55:22.440 --> 55:27.320
Trailers definitely
have an intelligence.

55:27.360 --> 55:29.760
They have a mind of their own
and it's a vindictive mind.

55:29.800 --> 55:31.480
It wants you to fail.

55:34.640 --> 55:36.760
JEREMY: And, thanks
to its vindictiveness,

55:36.800 --> 55:39.680
all of my lead in this
important race was gone.

55:44.440 --> 55:46.840
Quite ballsy of
Land Rover, really,

55:46.880 --> 55:51.600
to build a car that doesn't
have a low-ratio gearbox.

55:51.640 --> 55:53.960
But there is a lot of
electronically-controlled
stuff.

55:54.000 --> 55:56.760
The central diff,
for example - it just
locked for me then.

55:56.800 --> 55:59.560
I can feel it
working stuff out,

55:59.600 --> 56:01.880
finding the grip
on different wheels.

56:03.320 --> 56:05.200
And it works: look at that.

56:09.360 --> 56:11.360
My off-road work
is exceptional.

56:14.000 --> 56:16.880
How long before James May
says keep your thumbs
out of the steering wheel?

56:16.920 --> 56:19.400
It's all he knows
about off-roading.

56:19.440 --> 56:22.400
Thumbs outside
the steering wheel
in case it kicks.

56:24.400 --> 56:27.080
Mud ruts selected.

56:27.120 --> 56:29.880
Just because it's gone
a bit slippery.

56:29.920 --> 56:33.800
JAMES: But then,
I too hit a dead end.

56:33.840 --> 56:35.040
Oh, cock.

56:37.000 --> 56:39.160
Right, trailer reversing tip,

56:39.200 --> 56:43.360
if I look in the mirror
and I say I want
the boat to go that side,

56:43.400 --> 56:45.360
I lift that hand.

56:45.400 --> 56:47.640
So you look in the mirror.
So I'll do that...

56:54.640 --> 56:56.320
Right,
well, I am getting closer

56:56.360 --> 56:57.960
according to
my electronic compass.

56:58.000 --> 56:59.320
This is looking good.

57:00.720 --> 57:02.720
I've just gotta hope
they don't find this track.

57:04.680 --> 57:08.760
To be honest, in the Raptor,
I didn't need a track.

57:10.440 --> 57:11.960
I'm not a fan of
pickup trucks

57:12.000 --> 57:14.240
and I will kill you
if you ever tell
Richard Hammond this,

57:14.280 --> 57:15.840
but this is impressive.

57:17.280 --> 57:19.560
It's just drumming its
fingers coming along here.

57:19.600 --> 57:22.440
I mean, if I'd have asked it
to tow a battleship,

57:22.480 --> 57:26.240
maybe it would be
struggling a bit,
but a speedboat? Pah.

57:31.800 --> 57:34.120
Yes! Well done you,
little car!

57:36.000 --> 57:37.880
Do you know,
I'm gonna win this.

57:39.520 --> 57:41.200
Oh, hang on a minute.

57:44.240 --> 57:46.880
This thing's telling me,
it must be the other
side of the lake.

57:49.280 --> 57:50.520
I can see a flag.

57:50.560 --> 57:52.000
There's a flag. It's there.

57:53.360 --> 57:54.920
Clearly,
it would be impossible

57:54.960 --> 57:57.960
to drive the Macan
round the shoreline.

57:58.000 --> 58:02.280
So I needed
to break out the map
and find another route.

58:02.320 --> 58:04.160
A track, a track, a track.
There will be one.

58:05.720 --> 58:07.800
Oh...
Oh, good.

58:09.720 --> 58:11.760
JEREMY:
Why've you stopped here?
Finish line's over there.

58:11.800 --> 58:14.920
Yes, I know, I'm just
working out how to get there!

58:14.960 --> 58:17.680
You just drive round the
outside, look, on the beach.

58:17.720 --> 58:19.320
I can't do that.

58:19.360 --> 58:21.080
That's cos you're
in the wrong car.

58:21.120 --> 58:23.720
-No, you're in the wrong car.
-I'm not in the wrong car!

58:23.760 --> 58:26.360
You are!

58:26.400 --> 58:28.400
JEREMY: Rather
than have a pointless
debate about this,

58:30.080 --> 58:33.920
I decided to let
the Raptor do the talking.

58:33.960 --> 58:36.560
Here we go. Oh, yep.

58:38.000 --> 58:40.200
JAMES:
Meanwhile, very far back,

58:40.240 --> 58:41.840
in a blizzard, on a hill,

58:41.880 --> 58:44.280
the Velar's electronics,
predictably,

58:44.320 --> 58:46.360
were starting to struggle.

58:46.400 --> 58:50.280
Right, no traction launch.
Activate.

58:52.320 --> 58:54.240
Doesn't like it.

58:54.280 --> 58:55.920
Oh, no!

58:57.160 --> 59:00.040
I've gotta be honest,
I'm a bit disappointed.

59:00.080 --> 59:02.480
I'm using absolutely
everything on here.

59:05.280 --> 59:06.880
No.

59:10.320 --> 59:11.720
Come on. There you go.

59:14.760 --> 59:17.240
Oh! What's that big bump?

59:17.280 --> 59:19.520
This beach is woodier
than I thought.

59:20.960 --> 59:23.480
But the speedboat is still
upright, and that's good.

59:23.520 --> 59:25.800
And round we go.

59:27.680 --> 59:30.920
Ooh. Oh, no, no, no, no, no!

59:30.960 --> 59:33.320
No! Bloody hell!

59:35.240 --> 59:37.480
Distance, reducing.

59:37.520 --> 59:40.520
Hill descent control
is automatically on.

59:40.560 --> 59:43.360
Controlling the speed
with my thumb.

59:43.400 --> 59:47.480
It's excellent at going down
hills, this Range Rover.

59:47.520 --> 59:49.200
Not so sure
about it going up them.

59:49.240 --> 59:53.080
JEREMY: Having righted
the boat with no help
from any of the film crew...

59:55.840 --> 59:58.240
I was back on the move.

59:59.640 --> 1:00:02.080
Stop just dithering about.

1:00:03.560 --> 1:00:05.120
Ooh, God!

1:00:10.800 --> 1:00:12.440
Found it.

1:00:13.640 --> 1:00:16.120
This is what we need.

1:00:16.160 --> 1:00:18.560
Proper track.
It's farther from the lake,
I'll have further to go

1:00:18.600 --> 1:00:20.920
but I can get a move on.

1:00:20.960 --> 1:00:22.680
Now we've got
a race on our hands.

1:00:24.040 --> 1:00:26.600
JAMES: Eventually,
I arrived at the lake,

1:00:26.640 --> 1:00:28.840
but I wasn't worried
about how far back I was

1:00:28.880 --> 1:00:32.080
because I'd had an idea.

1:00:33.440 --> 1:00:35.400
That message from Mr Willman,

1:00:35.440 --> 1:00:38.680
it said the first person
to get to the finishing
line, didn't it?

1:00:38.720 --> 1:00:40.360
-Yes.

1:00:40.400 --> 1:00:43.080
The first person. Didn't
say anything about the car.

1:00:43.120 --> 1:00:47.560
So why don't I just unload
the boat and boat across?

1:00:47.600 --> 1:00:50.680
JEREMY: Meanwhile,
I'd left the difficult beach
through a wood

1:00:52.280 --> 1:00:56.000
and was on a track
with a problem.

1:00:56.040 --> 1:00:59.080
My vindictive trailer has now
decided to have a puncture.

1:01:02.360 --> 1:01:06.000
Well, I'm going to pay
it back by not stopping
cos I haven't got time.

1:01:06.040 --> 1:01:10.800
JEREMY: I didn't even stop
when the vindictive trailer
decided to be on fire.

1:01:20.760 --> 1:01:22.760
Oh, I'm gonna
lose that outboard.

1:01:29.680 --> 1:01:30.920
Boat suit.

1:01:36.160 --> 1:01:40.520
One wheel on my wagon
and I'm still rolling along.

1:01:40.560 --> 1:01:43.880
This is good.
This is very good.

1:01:43.920 --> 1:01:45.720
But then...

1:01:45.760 --> 1:01:47.360
Bloody hell.

1:01:47.400 --> 1:01:49.720
No! I'm in another dead end!

1:01:51.080 --> 1:01:52.880
There was only
one thing for it:

1:01:52.920 --> 1:01:55.400
another manual
three-point turn.

1:02:01.440 --> 1:02:06.440
This steel's just so
warm and comfortable!

1:02:11.040 --> 1:02:13.240
Whoa! Come on!

1:02:14.480 --> 1:02:15.760
Drifting my boat.

1:02:29.320 --> 1:02:30.920
I'm 57.

1:02:34.000 --> 1:02:35.800
No! No, no!

1:02:44.560 --> 1:02:46.240
Come on, come on, come on.

1:02:47.280 --> 1:02:48.920
Right.

1:02:48.960 --> 1:02:52.040
JAMES: Meanwhile, I was
ready for the final charge.

1:02:52.080 --> 1:02:53.640
Goodbye, losers.

1:02:53.680 --> 1:02:56.520
Ignition, start!

1:03:03.680 --> 1:03:06.520
Oh, cock.

1:03:08.200 --> 1:03:11.400
I'm just going
as fast as I dare.

1:03:15.520 --> 1:03:17.760
Speed... speed power.

1:03:20.120 --> 1:03:22.440
JAMES: With the other
two heading for failure,

1:03:22.480 --> 1:03:24.960
I got HMS Orange started

1:03:25.000 --> 1:03:28.360
and was cruising
to an easy win.

1:03:28.400 --> 1:03:29.880
This is just brilliant.

1:03:29.920 --> 1:03:31.720
Full throttle!

1:03:42.800 --> 1:03:44.280
Oh, cock.

1:03:44.320 --> 1:03:47.240
The boat is beginning
to behave oddly!

1:03:47.280 --> 1:03:51.360
There is a bit
of water coming in,
but it's not very far.

1:03:57.680 --> 1:03:59.200
Come on!

1:04:03.760 --> 1:04:05.120
There's the flag!

1:04:08.200 --> 1:04:10.960
Oh, really?

1:04:11.000 --> 1:04:12.720
Los-er!

1:04:12.760 --> 1:04:15.440
Oh, God.

1:04:15.480 --> 1:04:17.880
-Well, hang on a minute.

1:04:17.920 --> 1:04:19.320
Where's your boat?

1:04:19.360 --> 1:04:21.400
-It's there.
-No, it's not.

1:04:21.440 --> 1:04:23.720
It's just some bits of boat!

1:04:23.760 --> 1:04:26.200
It's a boat jigsaw.

1:04:26.240 --> 1:04:28.960
So you're finishing this race
without your car,

1:04:29.000 --> 1:04:31.800
without your trailer or
the boat that was on it...

1:04:31.840 --> 1:04:34.080
-I have got the boat!
-You've got
some bits of boat.

1:04:34.120 --> 1:04:36.200
-You're claiming
to be the winner.
-Listen.

1:04:36.240 --> 1:04:38.640
You've come second,
you're taking it badly.

1:04:38.680 --> 1:04:40.560
I think it doesn't matter

1:04:40.600 --> 1:04:43.760
because an even
more interesting race

1:04:43.800 --> 1:04:46.560
is developing out on
the water as we speak.

1:04:48.200 --> 1:04:50.800
Handling is affected
by water ingress!

1:04:50.840 --> 1:04:52.800
It's getting closer
to my kneecaps!

1:04:52.840 --> 1:04:55.640
Oh, Canadian flag, come on!

1:04:55.680 --> 1:05:00.160
Will he make it to the
finish point before he sinks?

1:05:00.200 --> 1:05:02.800
-That's got some tension
in it, hasn't it?
-I know!

1:05:02.840 --> 1:05:04.800
There's no tension here,
this is done.

1:05:04.840 --> 1:05:06.920
-Oh, yeah,
this is very tense.
-But we'll give you more.

1:05:06.960 --> 1:05:08.680
You two! Help!

1:05:08.720 --> 1:05:11.680
Come and rescue!
I'm going down!

1:05:11.720 --> 1:05:13.880
My boat's smashed
to pieces, James,

1:05:13.920 --> 1:05:15.440
I can't help you with that.

1:05:15.480 --> 1:05:19.600
My boat's, look,
it'll take me ages.
It's all the way over there!

1:05:19.640 --> 1:05:21.520
It's going down!

1:05:21.560 --> 1:05:24.480
I'd have to move mine
out of the way...

1:05:24.520 --> 1:05:27.120
And then I'd have
to walk up there,
along those rocks...

1:05:27.160 --> 1:05:30.360
It's gone! Oh, Jesus, ah!

1:05:30.400 --> 1:05:32.000
It's so cold!

1:05:32.040 --> 1:05:34.800
JEREMY: Look, he's going...
-Argh, you bastard!

1:05:34.840 --> 1:05:36.360
JEREMY: Have you ever seen...

1:05:36.400 --> 1:05:38.480
Argh! My testicles
are retreating!

1:05:38.520 --> 1:05:40.360
We don't need to know that!

1:05:40.400 --> 1:05:42.360
-Oh, no!

1:05:42.400 --> 1:05:44.520
-Ooh!
-Oh! Oh!

1:05:44.560 --> 1:05:46.400
That hurt me just watching!

1:05:46.440 --> 1:05:48.720
I've got a runny nose
thinking of it.

1:05:48.760 --> 1:05:50.000
My bits just shrivelled!

1:05:51.280 --> 1:05:54.080
-That was a cold, cold day.

1:05:54.120 --> 1:05:56.640
-I wouldn't want to be
in that water.

1:05:56.680 --> 1:05:59.560
-You couldn't help.
-l really wouldn't.

1:06:02.480 --> 1:06:06.760
What that film proves is
that if you want to buy
a Range Rover Velar

1:06:06.800 --> 1:06:08.840
or a Stelvio or a Macan,

1:06:08.880 --> 1:06:11.280
you're better off
with a Ford Raptor.

1:06:11.320 --> 1:06:15.440
Yeah, not only that,
the Raptor is actually
nearly half the price.

1:06:15.480 --> 1:06:18.440
Yes, but you can't
buy a Raptor in Britain.

1:06:18.480 --> 1:06:20.720
And so, on that terrible
disappointment,

1:06:20.760 --> 1:06:23.600
for you lot, at least,
it's time to end.

1:06:23.640 --> 1:06:25.440
Thank you so much
for watching, goodbye!
